{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17629389","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17629389"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:06:00+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:06:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17269"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17269","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17269"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9959"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69658"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9959","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9959"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17269"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55110"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"3078"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"10761"},{"type":"tags","id":"10763"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23345"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23432"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26664"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69658","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/69658"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EHuntington disease is an autosomal dominant neurodegenerative disorder that typically manifests between 30-50 years of age. Despite being lethal, the disease-causing mutation persists in human populations at a relatively stable frequency.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best explains why natural selection has not eliminated the Huntington disease mutation from human populations?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Mutation provides survival advantage in heterozygotes","Disease symptoms are becoming less severe over time","Mutation rate exactly balances selection pressure","Disease symptoms appear after most carriers have reproduced","Disease occurs too rarely to be affected by selection"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe persistence of Huntington disease in populations is primarily explained because \u003Cstrong\u003Edisease symptoms appear after most carriers have reproduced\u003C/strong\u003E. Since the condition typically manifests in middle age, affected individuals have usually already passed on their genes before becoming symptomatic, reducing selective pressure against the mutation.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cul\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMutation provides survival advantage in heterozygotes\u003C/strong\u003E - Unlike sickle cell trait, there is no known benefit to carrying the Huntington mutation\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDisease occurs too rarely to be affected by selection\u003C/strong\u003E - Selection can act on even rare variants if they significantly impact fitness\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMutation rate exactly balances selection pressure\u003C/strong\u003E - The mutation rate is not high enough to explain the persistence of the allele\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDisease symptoms are becoming less severe over time\u003C/strong\u003E - There is no evidence for reduced severity over generations\u003C/li\u003E    \u003C/ul\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EThis demonstrates an important principle of natural selection - traits that manifest after reproduction face reduced selective pressure compared to those affecting survival or reproduction earlier in life.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Natural selection acts on phenotypes that affect reproductive success and survival.","Selection pressure is strongest on traits expressed before or during reproductive years.","Harmful mutations that manifest after reproduction has occurred experience reduced selection pressure."],"references":["Schulte J, Littleton JT. The biological function of the Huntingtin protein and its relevance to Huntington\u0027s Disease pathology. Curr Trends Neurol. 2011 Jan 1;5:65-78. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC3237673/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55110"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17269"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55110","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55110"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-12T11:54:25+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-12T12:07:24+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9959"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69658"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position"